<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-05-11T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-05-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="1039" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1039">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 125.8273/41.</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">Consul <persName type="from">Canada</persName> to
                                    the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Extract.]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">American Consulate</hi>, <lb/>
                                        <hi rend="italic">Vera Cruz</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-05-11">
                                        <hi rend="italic">May 11, 1914</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>Joseph A. Marchani, clerk in American Consulate, Saltillo, arrived
                                here this morning. Reports all Americans reported arrested now
                                released with exception Vice Consul Silliman. Marchani left Saltillo
                                May 8; states was taken from jail to Consulate under heavy guard and
                                compelled under threat of death open safe and deliver all records
                                including Red Code and three hundred pesos and jewelry left at
                                Consulate for safe keeping. Believes copies of Red Code being made
                                for distribution among federal officers. Consulate now held by guard
                                of hundred federals.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Canada</hi></signed>.</closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>